                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14144222" author="jmspaggi" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 02:34:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yep, I so agree on that! But they are almot all over the place... Are you going to propose a patch for all? Might be difficult to integrate. Maybe this should be itself an umbrella or 12058 and we should devide that by sections? (Server, client, common, it, etc.)?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14144285" author="vrodionov" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 03:56:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I am thinking about automated routine, that will process all files. I will do everything locally, including all unit tests and when its ready, we will freeze the master for all commits except this one. Will it works? &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14144287" author="vrodionov" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 03:59:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Another approach is incremental patching. One patch for group of files. Sections are one possible way of grouping , but groups are large here.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14144316" author="stack" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 04:29:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Freezing commits while a big one lands is no problem.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145115" author="ndimiduk" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 17:47:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Could this be broken out into a couple critical path commits, or by package? Rolling back such a big commit down the road (for whatever reason) sounds like a painfully manual process.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145180" author="apurtell" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 18:27:40 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Could this be broken out into a couple critical path commits, or by package?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&apos;s a shame that JIRA does not let one nest subtasks in subtasks but we could file a subtask on the parent and link it here. The parent subtask &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-12023&quot; title=&quot;HRegion.applyFamilyMapToMemstore creates too many iterator objects.&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-12023&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-12023&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; is already an example of that with respect to &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-12060&quot; title=&quot;Replace enhanced for statement with basic for statement where possible&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-12060&quot;&gt;HBASE-12060&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145203" author="enis" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 18:36:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think the practice we try to follow so far was use wrappers for DEBUG, and TRACE calls, but not for INFO or any level higher. The assumption is that mostly INFO level or WARN level is on anyways. Do we want to do the wrapper for every level?  &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145207" author="apurtell" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 18:39:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Maybe INFO and below ?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145215" author="jmspaggi" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 18:41:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 for INFO and below. I have seen many places where the moved to WARN to reduce log size.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145241" author="vrodionov" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 18:56:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, most places (on critical paths) for DEBUG/TRACE are already wrapped. Do not have stats, but if they are not wrapped - they are not on critical path. This is mostly for INFO and for some rare cases (which are still possible) where we do not have wrappers for DEBUG/TRACE but should. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145251" author="stack" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 19:00:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;When would we ever turn off INFO-level logging?  Or WARN-level logging?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14145260" author="apurtell" created="Tue, 23 Sep 2014 19:04:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think we would ever turn off WARN level logging. I&apos;ve run with INFO level logging off before in production to manage log growth. There are alternative ways to achieve that end of course.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
